<article>
  <span class="badge badge-danger">BYPASS</span>
  <h2>3. Trusted Types Doesn't Help (Today)</h2>

  <div class="csp-indicator csp-on">
    ● Trusted Types: ON — <code>require-trusted-types-for 'script'; trusted-types dompurify lit-html</code>
  </div>

  <p>
    This page enforces Trusted Types via a <code>Content-Security-Policy</code> meta tag.
    Normally, this would block any raw string from being assigned to <code>innerHTML</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>But the alert still fires.</strong> Why? Lit registers a <code>'lit-html'</code>
    Trusted Types policy at startup — a no-op identity function:
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-label">lit-html.ts:263–267 — the internal no-op policy</div>
{% highlight "javascript" %}
const policy = trustedTypes
  ? trustedTypes.createPolicy('lit-html', {
      createHTML: (s) => s,  // identity function — blesses any string!
    })
  : undefined;
{% endhighlight %}
  </div>

  <p>
    <code>unsafeHTML</code> feeds the raw XSS string through this policy, converting
    it to <code>TrustedHTML</code> — then Lit sets <code>innerHTML</code> with it.
    Trusted Types is satisfied, but the browser still executes the payload.
  </p>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-block-label">demo-3.js — what you're running</div>
{% highlight "javascript" %}
import { html, render } from 'lit-html';
import { unsafeHTML } from 'lit-html/directives/unsafe-html.js';

// Trusted Types is active on this page, but unsafeHTML bypasses it via
// Lit's internal 'lit-html' policy (createHTML: s => s).
const payload = `<img src=x onerror="alert('TT bypass!')">`;

render(
  html`<div>${unsafeHTML(payload)}</div>`,
  document.querySelector('#result')
);
{% endhighlight %}
  </div>

  <div class="demo-area">
    <h3>Interactive Demo</h3>
    <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:#546e7a;margin-top:0">
      Open DevTools → Console. Trusted Types is active but the alert fires anyway.
    </p>
    <button class="run-btn" id="run-btn">Run Demo</button>
    <div class="result-box" id="result">
      <em style="color:#999">Output will appear here after clicking "Run Demo".</em>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p style="margin-top:1.5rem">
    This is the core of the problem: Lit's <code>'lit-html'</code> policy acts as a
    universal bypass, defeating the browser's injection-sink enforcement for all
    <code>unsafeHTML()</code> calls.
  </p>

